card.name: Beta Test (present to out buyer)
card.desc: Here we begin to present our product to the end user for first testing and get the first impressions and feedback to improve the product so that they are satisfied with it.

card.name: Further testing in extreme conditions
card.desc: In this stage we test the possible alternative paths that the system can take and if they're working as expected. If there were no faults (which is unlikely to happen but we can still dream), we continue to the beta test.

card.desc: Here we plan on testing every functionality as a unit of the whole system. Unit tests will be regressively initiated, so as we further develop and add new features, we can see, if the existing code still operates successfully.

card.name: Sequence diagrams
card.desc: Here we take the start vision, the DPU model, but mainly the PU specifications and activity diagrams to draw this relatively hard sequence diagrams; the intent of which is to show in detail on how the maing business logic will work. It's focus is not so much on what the chosen use case does, but how does it do it, we defined the so called life lines, the actor and its interaction with the system, possible alternative paths and feedback to the actor, and the names for the classes which we plan on implementing in the future. It also includes a subtle reference to the DB and method calls.

card.name: Activity diagrams
card.desc: We created these diagrams based on our original product vision, the PU specifications aswell as the DPU model; it looks in detail on how each use case in the DPU model works (its activity - hence the name), its actions, data, paths and merges of them, etc....

card.name: PU specifications
card.desc: For each use case (in the created DPU model), we define the specification: a short description, the primary and secondary actors, possible needed conditions for excecution, the main course of execution, the state of the system after the excection and any alternative paths for when the main course of excectuion is not possible.

card.name: DPU model
card.desc: We draw the DPU model (based on use case definitions), which is going to be the basis for further development.

card.desc: In this stage, we define the use cases for our system (based on the main features, defined in the vision previously).

card.desc: Analysing the market for possible competitors, as well as comparing our solution to the problem with their solutions.

card.name: Describing needs and features
card.desc: Specifiying the main features of our product, the priorities of their development, how it will work and when is it going to be released.

card.name: Describing the environment

card.desc: Defining everyone involved in our products (passively and actively), their descriptions and responsibilities.
